]\n* [[Amelia Rose Blaire]]\n* Gregg Daniel\n* [[Aaron Christian Howles]]\n* [[Noah Matthews]]\n* [[Bailey Noble]]\n* [[Nathan Parsons]]\n* [[Karolina Wydra]]\n* [[Tara Buck]]\n}}\n| executive_producer       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]]\n* [[Gregg Fienberg]]\n* [[Brian Buckner]]\n* [[Raelle Tucker]]\n* [[Alexander Woo]]\n* [[Nancy Oliver]]\n* [[Mark Hudis]]\n* [[Angela Robinson (director)|Angela Robinson]]\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plain list|\n* Christina Jokanovich (co-producer)\n* David Auge (co-producer)\n* Marlis Pujol (co-producer)\n* Luis M. Pati\u00f1o (associate producer)\n* Bruce Dunn\n* W. Mark McNair\n* Carol Dunn Tussell\n}}\n| company                  = Your Face Goes Here Entertainment\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Domestic Television]]\n| runtime                  = 45\u201360 minutes\n| channel                  = [[HBO]]\n| first_aired              = September 7, 2008\n| last_aired               = August 24, 2014\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = http://www.hbo.com/trueblood/\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''True Blood''''' is<!--Not \"was\", per [[WP:TENSE]] and [[WP:MOS]]--> an American [[fantasy]] [[Horror fiction|horror]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[television series]] produced and created by [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]]. It was based on ''[[The Southern Vampire Mysteries]]'', a series of novels by [[Charlaine Harris]].\n\nThe series revolves around [[Sookie Stackhouse]] ([[Anna Paquin]]), a [[telepathic]] waitress living in the fictional rural town of Bon Temps, Louisiana and is set two years after the invention of a synthetic blood product branded \u201cTru Blood\u201d that has allowed vampires to \"come out of the coffin\" and let their presence to be known to mankind, chronicling the vampires' struggle for equal rights and assimilation, while anti-vampire organizations begin to gain power. Sookie's world is turned upside down when she falls in love with 173-year-old vampire [[Bill Compton (The Southern Vampire Mysteries)|Bill Compton]] ([[Stephen Moyer]]), and for the first time, she must navigate the trials and terrors of intimacy and relationships.<ref name=\"HBO roles with\" /><ref name=\"Ball bringing\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i0181f5a5ab18b1585b313d1d7524c51a |title=Ball bringing new 'Blood' to HBO |accessdate=March 20, 2008 |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=August 10, 2007 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080410175109/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i0181f5a5ab18b1585b313d1d7524c51a <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe show was broadcast on the premium cable network [[HBO]], in the United States, and was produced by HBO in association with Ball's production company, Your Face Goes Here Entertainment.<ref name=\"HBO roles with\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969971.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 |title=HBO rolls with Ball's 'True Blood' |accessdate=March 20, 2008 |last=Schneider |first=Michael |date=August 9, 2007 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]]}}</ref> The series premiered on September 7, 2008 and concluded on August 24, 2014, comprising seven seasons and 80 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/07/true-blood-renewed-season-7-hbo/# |title=HBO Renews True Blood for Seventh Season |publisher=Daily Dead |date= |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.screenspy.com/industrynews/true-blood-to-end-its-run-in-2014/|title = True Blood to End its Run in 2014|last = The Screen Spy Team|date = September 3, 2013|publisher = Screen Spy}}</ref> The first five seasons received highly positive reviews, and both nominations and wins for several awards, including a [[Golden Globe]] and an [[Emmy]].\n\n==Series overview==\n{{Main|List of True Blood episodes}}\n{{:List of True Blood episodes}}\nThe [[fictional universe]] depicted in the series is premised on the notion that [[vampire]]s exist, unbeknownst to the majority of humans until two years before the series premiere, when the creation of synthetic blood (\"Tru Blood\") by Japanese scientists, which eliminated vampires' need for human blood to survive, allowed vampires to \"come out of the coffin\" and reveal their existence to the world.{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} This so-called \"Great Revelation\" has split vampires into two camps: those who wish to integrate into human society (i.e., \"mainstream\") by campaigning for citizenship and equal rights,{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} and those who think human-vampire co-existence is impossible, because it conflicts with the inherently predatory and violent nature of vampires. It has also caused similar divisions amongst non-vampires; some believe that vampires should be accepted and granted rights, while others view them as monsters to be destroyed. Throughout the series, other [[supernatural]] creatures are introduced, among them [[Shapeshifting|shapeshifters]], [[Werewolf|werewolves]], [[Fairy|faeries]], [[Witchcraft|witches]], and a [[maenad]].\n\nThe series revolves around Sookie Stackhouse ([[Anna Paquin]]), a [[telepathy|telepathic]] human-faerie hybrid known as a halfling (not to be confused with similarly named, but unrelated [[halfling|creatures]] found in other fantasy works). Sookie is a waitress at Merlotte's Bar and Grill, owned by [[Sam Merlotte]] ([[Sam Trammell]]) in the small [[Louisiana]] town of Bon Temps. Sam is a shapeshifter, though this secret is kept hidden from most of the town. Other characters include [[Bill Compton (The Southern Vampire Mysteries)|Bill Compton]] ([[Stephen Moyer]]), a 173-year-old vampire who has returned to Bon Temps to take up residence in his former home following the death of his last remaining relative; [[Tara Thornton]] ([[Rutina Wesley]]), Sookie's tough-talking but insecure best friend; [[Jason Stackhouse|Jason]] ([[Ryan Kwanten]]), Sookie's womanizing brother; [[Eric Northman]] ([[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]]), a 1000-year-old vampire and Sheriff of Area 5; and [[Lafayette Reynolds]] ([[Nelsan Ellis]]), a [[short order cook]], drug dealer, road crew member, and [[medium (spirituality)|medium]].\n\nThe show explores several contemporary issues such as the struggle for equal rights, discrimination, and violence against minorities and homosexuals, the problems of drug addiction, the power of faith and religion, the control/influence of the media, the quest for identity, and the importance of family.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development history===\nSeries creator [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]] had previously worked with the cable channel HBO on ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', which ran for five seasons. In October 2005, after ''Six Feet Under'' wrapped, Ball signed a two-year agreement with HBO to develop and produce original programming for the network. ''True Blood'' became the first project under the deal after Ball became acquainted with [[Charlaine Harris]]'s Southern Vampire Mystery books.<ref name=\"press release\">{{cite press release |title= Concludes Exclusive Two-Year Television Deal with ''Six Feet Under'' Creator Alan Ball |publisher= [[Time Warner]], of which HBO is a subsidiary |date=October 31, 2005 |url=http://www.timewarner.com/corp/newsroom/pr/0,20812,1124432,00.html |accessdate=March 20, 2008}}</ref> One day, while early for a dental appointment, Ball was browsing through a [[Barnes & Noble]] bookshop and came across ''[[Dead Until Dark]]'' (2001), the first installment in Harris' series. He read the entries that followed and became interested in \"bringing [Harris'] vision to television\".<ref name=\"press release\"/><ref name=\"IGN paley fest\">{{cite web | first=Matt | last=Fowler | title=Bloody Bites from True Blood Season 2 | date=June 12, 2001 | website=IGN | url =http://tv.ign.com/articles/972/972562p1.html |accessdate=June 7, 2002}}</ref> Having already had two other adaptation options for the books, Harris said she chose to work with him, though, because \"[Ball] really 'got' me. That's how he convinced me to go with him. I just felt that he understood what I was doing with the books.\"{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe project's hour-long [[Pilot (TV)|pilot]] was ordered concurrently with the completion of the development deal. It was written, directed, and produced by Ball.<ref name=\"HBO roles with\" /><ref name=\"press release\" /> Cast members Paquin, Kwanten, and Trammell were announced in February 2007, and Moyer later in April.<ref name=\"Paquin finds\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i72ff675fda9c3c4bb99995e58e86eb35 |title=Paquin finds 'True' calling for Ball, HBO |accessdate=September 20, 2010 |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=February 26, 2007 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323060042/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i72ff675fda9c3c4bb99995e58e86eb35 |archivedate=March 23, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Moyer, HBO make 'Blood' pact|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moyer-hbo-make-blood-pact-133609|website = The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate = February 23, 2016}}</ref> The pilot was shot in the early summer of 2007 and was officially ordered to series in August, at which point Ball had already written more episodes.<ref name=\"HBO roles with\" /> Production on the series began later that fall,<ref>{{cite news |last= Mitovitch |first= Matt Webb |title= ''True Blood'' Vampire Saga Tests Positive at HBO |work=[[TV Guide]] |url= http://www.tvguide.com/news/True-Blood-Vampire-16079.aspx |date= August 10, 2007 |accessdate=August 17, 2008}}</ref> with [[Brook Kerr]], who portrayed Tara Thornton in the original pilot, replaced by [[Rutina Wesley]].<ref name='Futon review'>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/reviews/2008/06/05/the-futons-first-look-true-blood-hbo-27770/20080605_trueblood/ |title=Rants & Reviews&nbsp;\u2013 The Futon Critic's First Look: \"True Blood\" (HBO) |accessdate=June 16, 2014 |last=Ford Sullivan |first=Brian |date=June 5, 2008 |website=The Futon Critic }}</ref> Two more episodes of the series had been filmed before the [[2007-08 Writers Guild of America strike]] shut down production of the 12-episode first season until February 2008.<ref>{{cite news | title=The TV Grid: Is your show coming back? | url =http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/business/la-striketvgrid-html,1,316783.htmlstory?coll=la-utilities-entnews | work =[[LA Times]] | pages = |accessdate=May 2, 2009 | language = | date=December 20, 2007}}</ref> That September, after only the first two episodes of the series had aired, HBO placed an order for a second season of 12 episodes, with production scheduled to commence in January 2009 for a summer premiere.<ref>{{cite news |title=HBO renews 'True Blood' | date=September 17, 2008 | url =http://www.thrfeed.com/2008/09/hbo-renews-true.html | work =[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=May 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Title sequence===\n''True Blood'''s Emmy-nominated title sequence is composed of portrayals of the show's [[Deep South]] setting, and runs to \"[[Bad Things (Jace Everett song)|Bad Things]]\" by [[Jace Everett]]. The original featurette was created around the [[Jennifer Herrema]] ([[Royal Trux]]) song \"RadTimesXpress\".<ref name='Doing baptisms'>{{cite news |title=Doing Baptisms, Bars, and Bloodlust |date=September 10, 2008 |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/entertainment/1550089/doing_baptisms_bars_and_bloodlust/index.html |accessdate=May 2, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100417231146/http://www.redorbit.com/news/entertainment/1550089/doing_baptisms_bars_and_bloodlust/index.html |archive-date=April 17, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:True Blood Opening Sequence.jpg|thumb|The makers of the title sequence wanted to explore themes of redemption and forgiveness.]]\n\nConceptually, the sequence was constructed around the idea of \"the whore in the house of prayer\"<ref name='DK feature'>{{cite web |url=http://news.creativeleague.com/feature-dks-true-blood-the-making-of/ |title=Feature: DK's True Blood \u2013 The Making Of |accessdate=May 2, 2009 |work=Creative League News |publisher=Creative League |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204135231/http://news.creativeleague.com/feature-dks-true-blood-the-making-of |archive-date=December 4, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> by intermingling contradictory images of sex, violence, and religion and displaying them from the point of view of \"a [[supernatural]], predatory creature observing human beings from the shadows ...\"<ref name='Doing baptisms'/> Ideas of redemption and forgiveness are also explored, and thus the sequence progresses from morning to night and culminates in a [[baptism]].<ref name='DK feature'/>\n\nThe title sequence was created by the independent film company Digital Kitchen. The sequence also features images and themes of death and rebirth; the circle of life. A [[Venus fly-trap]] can be seen engulfing a frog, while the rotting of a fox's head is sped up to reveal maggots feeding off the corpse. Rebirth is represented by an image of a woman being \"washed clean\" from her sins in a lake, and a preacher blessing and possibly performing an exorcism on a member of his congregation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artofthetitle.com/2008/11/21/true-blood/ |title=True Blood opening title sequence |publisher=Art of the Title |date=November 21, 2008 |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSome of the footage used in the sequence was filmed on location. Digital Kitchen took a four-day trip to [[Louisiana]] to film; it also shot scenes at a [[Chicago]] church, and on a stage and in a bar in [[Seattle]].<ref name= 'DK feature'/>\n\nDuring editing, individual frames were splattered with drops of blood.<ref name= 'DK feature'/> The sequence's transitions were constructed differently; they were made with a [[Instant film|Polaroid]] transfer technique. The last frame of one shot and the first frame of another were taken as a single Polaroid photo, which was divided between [[emulsion]] and backing. The emulsion was filmed being further separated by chemicals, and those shots of this separation were placed back into the final edit.<ref name= 'Doing baptisms'/> Eight different typefaces, inspired by Southern road signs, were created manually for cast and crew credits, as well as the show's title card.<ref name= 'DK feature'/>\n\nIn a 2010 issue of ''[[TV Guide]]'', the show's opening title sequence ranked #5 on a list of TV's top 10 credits sequences, as selected by readers.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tomashoff, Craig|title=Credits Check|work=TV Guide|date= October 18, 2010|pages =16\u201317}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Gary Calamar]], who supervises the series' music, said his goal for the show's soundtrack is to create something \"swampy, bluesy and spooky\" and to feature local Louisiana musicians.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046944/five-tv-shows-to-enrich-the-ears-in-08 |title=Five TV Shows To Enrich The Ears In '08 by Chuck Crisafulli |magazine=Billboard.com |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref> ''True Blood'' soundtrack albums have twice earned [[Grammy Award]] nominations.\n\nComposer [[Nathan Barr]] writes the original score for the series, which features the cello, guitar, [[prepared piano]], and glass harmonica among other instruments, all of which he performs himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0056550/bio |title=Nathan Barr \u2013 Biography|accessdate=November 6, 2009|date= |last= |first= |work=[[Internet Movie Database]]}}</ref> The main theme song is \"Bad Things\" by [[country music]] artist [[Jace Everett]], from his 2005 self-titled debut.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20222109,00.html |title=True Blood \u2013 TV Review|accessdate=October 22, 2008|date= September 7, 2008|last=Tucker |first=Ken |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref>\n\nElektra/Atlantic Records released a ''True Blood'' soundtrack on May 19, 2009, the same day as the release of the DVD and Blu-ray of the first season.<ref>[http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/04/true-blood-cd.html \"'True Blood' soundtrack to feature Lucinda Williams, Ryan Adams, and more\"]\", [[Entertainment Weekly]]\", April 15, 2009. Retrieved April 15, 2009.</ref> Nathan Barr's original score for ''True Blood'' was released on CD on the [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] label on September 8, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://truebloodnet.com/nathan-barr-lisbeth-scott-releasing-true-blood-music-scores/ |title=Nathan Barr and Lisbeth Scott Releasing True Blood Music Scores |publisher=Truebloodnet.com |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> The second ''True Blood'' soundtrack was released on May 25, 2010, to coincide with the third season's premiere in June. The third volume was released on September 6, 2011, a few days before the season four finale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/true-blood/articles/true-blood-soundtrack-news-volume-3-release-date-is-sept-6 |title=True Blood Soundtrack News: Volume 3 Release Date Is Sept. 6 |publisher=Wetpaint.com |date=August 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBoth [[Nathan Barr]] and [[Jace Everett]] won 2009 awards from [[Broadcast Music Incorporated]] in the BMI Cable Awards category for, respectively, ''True Blood's'' original score and theme song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/538576 |title=BMI Film & Television Awards 2009 |publisher=Bmi.com |date=May 21, 2009 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe show's individual episode titles are named after songs featured in the episodes, usually heard during the closing credits. The title usually indicates something about the events that will unfold throughout the given episode. For example, episode ten of season four is titled \"[[Burning Down the House]]\", and the end credits feature a cover version of the classic [[Talking Heads]] song performed by [[The Used]].\n\n===Marketing===\n[[File:Truebloodopticalillusion.jpg|thumb|right|Promotional poster for second season]]\nThe premiere of ''True Blood'' was prefaced with a [[viral marketing]]/[[alternate reality game]] (ARG) campaign, based at BloodCopy.com, throughout the summer.<ref>Yoke, [http://yokedesign.com.au/blog/online-marketing-done-right-the-case-of-hbo-true-blood/ \"Online Marketing Done Right \u2013 the Case of HBO's True Blood\"], ''Yoke'', June 17, 2014. Retrieved July 13, 2015</ref> This included setting up multiple websites,<ref name=\"bloodcopy\">{{cite web\n| title = BloodCopy\n| accessdate=June 19, 2008\n| url = http://bloodcopy.com/\n}}</ref><ref name=\"rev\">{{cite web\n| title = RevenantOnes\n| accessdate=June 19, 2008\n| url = http://www.revenantones.com/\n}}</ref><ref name=\"chishio.jp\">{{cite web\n| title = Chishio.jp\n| accessdate=June 19, 2008\n| url = http://www.chishio.jp/\n}}</ref> encoding web address into unmarked envelopes mailed to high-profile blog writers and others, and even performances by a \"vampire\" who attempted to reach out to others of their kind, to discuss the recent creation of \"TrueBlood\", a fictional beverage featured in the show.\nA [[MySpace]] account with the username \"Blood\"<ref name=\"myspace-account\">{{cite web\n| title = MySpace.com \u2013 Blood \u2013 28 \u2013 Male \u2013 Shreveport, Louisiana\n| accessdate=June 19, 2008\n| url = http://profile.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=user.viewprofile&friendid=389839563\n}}</ref> had, as of June 19, uploaded two videos;<ref name=\"blood-videos\">{{cite web\n| title = MySpaceTV Videos: Blood Video Channel\n| accessdate=June 19, 2008\n| url = http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.channel&ChannelID=389839563\n}}</ref> one entitled \"Vampire Taste Test \u2013 True Blood vs Human\",<ref name=\"myspacevid1\">{{cite video\n| title = MySpaceTV Videos: Vampire Taste Test \u2013 Tru Blood vs Human by Blood\n| accessdate=June 19, 2008\n| time = 1:29\n| url = http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&videoid=36335810\n}}</ref> and one called \"BloodCopy Exclusive INTERVIEW WITH SAMSON THE VAMPIRE\".\nA [[prequel]] [[comic]] was handed out to attendees of the 2008 [[Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]]. The comic centers around an old vampire named Lamar, who tells the reader about how TruBlood surfaced and was discussed between many vampires before going public. At one point, Lamar wonders if TruBlood is making the world safe for vampires or from them. Several commercials featured on HBO and [[Facebook]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.new.facebook.com/video/video.php?v=608447658860#/video/?id=23768668081 | title=TruBlood's Videos |accessdate=September 14, 2008}}</ref> aired prior to the series premiere, placing vampires in ads similar to those of beer and wine.\n\nHBO produced and broadcast two documentaries to promote ''True Blood'', entitled \"True Bloodlines\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Turek |first=Ryan |url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=7555 |title=A Pair of True Blood Docs on the Way |publisher=Shocktillyoudrop.com |date=September 1, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> The first, ''Vampire Legends'', explored the earliest portrayals of vampires in legend, literature, and cinema. The second, ''A New Type'', discusses vampire culture from Nosferatu to today's sensual, sexual creatures. To that end, the show also covered the modern vampire subculture and real-life vampire clubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tlcoto.salemsloft.com/index.php?topic=1060.0 | title=HBO Documentaries |accessdate=June 22, 2010}}</ref> Actors and writers from ''True Blood'' appeared in the documentaries. The shows first aired on September 6, 2008, on HBO.\n\nThousands of DVDs of the first episode were handed out to attendees of Midnight Madness, a special film festival. [[Blockbuster Video]] provided free rental of the first episode of ''True Blood'' several days before it was broadcast on HBO.\n\nOn April 16, 2009, HBO released the first teaser poster for season 2. The image uses a perspective technique that shows observers one of two images.<ref>{{cite web | author=James Hibberd | title=Wicked new teaser poster for 'True Blood' season two| url=http://www.thrfeed.com/2009/04/new-teaser-poster-for-true-blood-season-two.html | publisher= The Live Feed}}</ref> A minute-long promotional video advertising season two, which featured [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Beyond Here Lies Nothin']]\", was released via ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' in early May.<ref>{{cite web |title= Watch the new ''True Blood'' promo here |publisher= SciFi Wire |date= May 2, 2009 |url= http://scifiwire.com/2009/05/watch-the-new-true-blood.php |accessdate=May 3, 2009}}</ref> There is also a website for The Fellowship of the Sun,<ref>{{cite web|author=HBO |url=http://fellowshipofthesun.org/ |title=Fellowshipofthesun.org |publisher=Fellowshipofthesun.org |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref> antagonists from the book series, featuring videos about hot-button issues such as becoming a vampire.\n\nIn September 2009, HBO filed a trademark registration with the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] for a possible future electronic game based on ''True Blood''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bailey |first=Kat |url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3176040 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719021321/http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3176040 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 19, 2012 |title=HBO Files Trademark For 'True Blood' Game |publisher=1up.com |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=June 5, 2012 }}</ref> The network then launched a ''True Blood'' jewelry line in collaboration with New York-based designer Udi Behr. Inspired by the series, the jewelry has a Gothic look and features sterling silver, polished steel, and rubies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brandweek.com/bw/content_display/news-and-features/direct/e3i0d52172227325f288887c9afa550db96 |title=HBO Bites Into Fashion With 'True Blood' Jewelry |publisher=Brandweek.com |date=May 30, 2012 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> In the same month, HBO.com began selling Tru:Blood, a beverage branded to resemble the fictional synthetic blood that appears in the show. The beverage is a carbonated blood orange-flavored drink, developed and manufactured by [[Omni Consumer Products (company)|Omni Consumer Products]], a company that specializes in defictionalizing brands from television and movies, and FMCG Manufacturing Company, a specialist manufacturer of licensed entertainment products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trubeverage.com/ |title=Trubeverage.com |publisher=Trubeverage.com |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Universitatea Bucure\u0219ti 2012-09-23 02-31-44.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The fountain in [[Bucharest]]'s [[University Square, Bucharest|University Square]] being colored in red for the premiere of 4th season]]\nIn June 2010, HBO held a special event at a number of movie theaters around the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/05/21/hbo-hosting-nationwide-true-blood-screening-events-on-june-1/52058|title=HBO Hosting Nationwide Screenings.|accessdate=June 22, 2010}}</ref> complete with red carpet, searchlights, and swag bags. Contest winners were invited to watch a live special, the Season 2 finale, a preview of Season 3, and a live interview on the set of ''True Blood'' with the cast and Alan Ball. HBO also began selling ''True Blood'' figural [[Bust (sculpture)|busts]] featuring Bill, Sookie, and Eric. Busts of other characters became available later.\n\nHBO and IDW Publishing announced at the 2010 WonderCon that they would be publishing a comic book based on the series.<ref>{{cite web|author=Reed Young |url=http://www.tvshowzonline.com/true-blood-season-7-major-character-gonna-die-in-the-first-episode/ |title=True Blood Season 7: Major Character Gonna Die in the First Episode |date= June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref> [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]] developed and wrote the comic. The first booklet, with a print run of 53,000, was released in July 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.hbo.com/detail.php?p=261204&v=hbo_shows_true-blood |title=True Blood #1 Comic Book |publisher=Store.hbo.com |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref> and soon sold out. The second issue went on sale August 18, 2010, with a second printing of the first issue going on sale August 25.<ref>{{cite web|last=Elfman |first=Mali |url=http://screencrave.com/2010-08-18/true-blood-comic-book-sold-out/ |title=True Blood Comic Book Sold Out! |publisher=Screencrave.com |date=August 18, 2010 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> Six comics were issued in the series, and they were compiled as the graphic novel ''All Together Now'' on February 15, 2011. This was the first in a series of four graphic novels released by [[HBO]] under the ''True Blood'' franchise and sold in major bookstores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://truebloodguide.com/2011/02/13/true-blood-graphic-novel/ |title=True Blood Graphic Novel |publisher=True Blood Guide |date=February 13, 2011 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> Ensuing titles include ''Tainted Love'', ''The French Quarter'', and ''Ongoing''.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:True Blood - 2011 International Comic-Con.jpg|thumb|Some of the cast of ''True Blood'' at the 2011 Comic-Con.]]\n{{Main|List of True Blood characters|l1=List of ''True Blood'' characters}}\n''True Blood'' employs a broad ensemble cast composed of regular, central characters and a rotating group of impermanent supporting characters. Though the series is based in the fictional town of Bon Temps, Louisiana, a noticeable number of the actors comprising the cast are originally from outside the United States. In an interview, Ball explained that he didn't intentionally seek out \"non-American\" actors, but was willing to go anywhere he needed to in order \"to find the actor who makes the character breathe\". Ball went on to explain that, in casting, there was more of a focus on who would portray the character in a compelling way rather than who would physically resemble the characters from the book. Noting that there's a definite difference between the characters and storylines portrayed in ''True Blood'' and the ones depicted in ''The Southern Vampire Mysteries'', he described Harris as being very understanding in terms of how her work was being reinterpreted.<ref name=\"Futon1\">{{cite news| last=Halterman | first=Jim| title = True Blood's Alan Ball talks sex, violence & vampires| newspaper = The Futon Critic| date = September 5, 2008| url = http://www.thefutoncritic.com/rant.aspx?id=20080905_trueblood | accessdate=September 1, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n===Main characters===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%; width:100%\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Actor\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Character\n! colspan=\"7\"| Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 3)|3]]\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 4)|4]]\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 5)|5]]\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 6)|6]]\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| [[True Blood (season 7)|7]]\n|-\n| [[Anna Paquin]]\n| [[Sookie Stackhouse]]\n| colspan=\"7\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Stephen Moyer]]\n| [[Bill Compton (The Southern Vampire Mysteries)|Bill Compton]]\n| colspan=\"7\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Sam Trammell]]\n| [[Sam Merlotte]]\n| colspan=\"7\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Ryan Kwanten]]\n| [[Jason Stackhouse]]\n| colspan=\"7\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Rutina Wesley]]\n| [[Tara 