]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Terry Bellefleur]]\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"5\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n|-\n| [[Michael McMillian]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Reverend Steve Newlin]]\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n|-\n| [[Deborah Ann Woll]]\n| [[Jessica Hamby]]\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"6\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Mariana Klaveno]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Lorena Krasiki]]\n| {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n| {{n/a|}}\n| {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Marshall Allman]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Tommy Mickens]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Kristin Bauer van Straten]]\n| [[Pamela Swynford De Beaufort|Pam Swynford de Beaufort]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"5\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Kevin Alejandro]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Jesus Velasquez]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Denis O'Hare]]\n| [[Russell Edgington]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Lindsay Pulsipher]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Crystal Norris]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Lauren Bowles]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Holly Cleary]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Janina Gavankar]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters#Luna Garza|Luna Garza]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Fiona Shaw]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Marnie Stonebrook]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Jessica Tuck]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Nan Flanagan]]\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| {{cGuest}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n|-\n| [[Joe Manganiello]]\n| [[Alcide Herveaux]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Scott Foley]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Patrick Devins]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Lucy Griffiths (actress, born 1986)|Lucy Griffiths]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters#Nora Gainesborough|Nora Gainesborough]]\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Christopher Meloni]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Roman Zimojic]]\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Valentina Cervi]]\n| [[List of True Blood characters|Salome Agrippa]]\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Rutger Hauer]]\n| [[Niall Brigant]]\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n\n|-\n| [[Arliss Howard]]\n| Truman Burrell\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Kelly Overton (actress)|Kelly Overton]]\n| Rikki Naylor\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| {{cMain}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Robert Patrick]]\n| Jackson Herveaux\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| {{cGuest|Special Guest}}\n|-\n| [[Rob Kazinsky]]\n| Macklyn Warlow\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Jurnee Smollett|Jurnee Smollett-Bell]]\n| Nicole Wright\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Amelia Rose Blaire]]\n| Willa Burrell\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| Gregg Daniel\n| Reverend Daniels\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Aaron Christian Howles]]\n| Rocky Cleary\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cGuest}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Noah Matthews]]\n| Wade Cleary\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cGuest}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Bailey Noble]]\n| Adilyn Bellefleur\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Luke Grimes]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| James Kent\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Nathan Parsons]]\n| colspan=\"6\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Karolina Wydra]]\n| Violet Mazurski\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Tara Buck]]\n| Ginger\n| {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cRecurring}}\n| {{cGuest}}\n| {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n|}\n;Cast notes:\n{{notelist}}\n\n<!-- This is for characters/actors who get main credits billing, please do not add minor characters -->\nThe major characters of the [[True Blood (season 1)|first season of ''True Blood'']] are introduced among various intertwining plot lines that surround the Bon Temps bar \"Merlotte's\". The show's main protagonist, [[Sookie Stackhouse]] ([[Anna Paquin]]), is a telepath and waitress at Merlotte's.{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} In the opening episode she saves Merlotte's first vampire customer, [[William \"Bill\" Comptom|Bill Compton]] ([[Stephen Moyer]]), when a local couple attempts to drain him of his blood (vampire blood is known on the show as a human narcotic: \"V\" or \"V Juice\").{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} Through the relationship that develops between Sookie and Bill, the viewer progressively learns more about vampire culture and the limitations of vampire physiology (e.g. susceptibility to silver and the sun).\n\nThe major plot of the first season revolves around the murder of several women connected to Sookie's older brother, [[Jason Stackhouse|Jason]] ([[Ryan Kwanten]]).{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} The women murdered include sexual partner Maudette Pickens (Danielle Sapia),{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} on-and-off romantic interest and Merlotte's waitress Dawn Green ([[Lynn Collins]]),{{ref|Mine|E-3}} grandmother [[Adele Stackhouse|Adele]] ([[Lois Smith]]) or simply \"Gran\",{{ref|Sparks|E-5}} and girlfriend [[Characters of True Blood#Amy Burley|Amy Burley]] ([[Lizzy Caplan]]).{{ref|Love Bury|E-11}} Though the viewer is always aware of Jason's innocence in their deaths, Detective [[Characters of True Blood#Andy Bellefleur|Andy Bellefleur]] ([[Chris Bauer]]) targets him as the prime suspect in the investigation he conducts with [[Characters of True Blood#Sheriff Bud Dearborne|Sheriff Bud Dearborne]] ([[William Sanderson]]) to identify their killer.{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} Jason's best friends and co-workers, [[Characters of True Blood#Hoyt Fortenberry|Hoyt Fortenberry]] ([[Jim Parrack]]) and [[Characters of True Blood#Rene Lenier|Rene Lenier]] ([[Michael Raymond-James]]) provide him with support despite the turmoil he encounters.{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} Rene, who becomes engaged to Merlotte's waitress [[Arlene Fowler]] ([[Carrie Preston]]),{{ref|Fourth|E-8}} is eventually exposed as the Bon Temps murderer and is killed in a final confrontation with Sookie.{{ref|You'll Be|E-12}}\n\nA secondary plot in the first season (that later develops as the primary storyline in the second) revolves around Sookie's best friend [[Tara Thornton]] ([[Rutina Wesley]]).{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} In the first episode, Tara is hired as a bartender at Merlotte's by bar owner, shapeshifter,{{ref|Don't Wanna|E-11}} and admirer of Sookie, [[Sam Merlotte]] ([[Sam Trammell]]),{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} with whom Tara later has a brief relationship.{{ref|Mine|E-3}} Tara's cousin [[Characters of True Blood#Lafayette Reynolds|Lafayette Reynolds]] ([[Nelsan Ellis]]) already works as a cook at Merlotte's{{ref|Strange Love|E-1}} (in addition to several other jobs that include road crew, prostitute, and drug dealer){{ref|Mine|E-3}} with Andy's cousin and [[Iraq War]] [[veteran]], [[List of True Blood characters#Terry Bellefleur|Terry]] ([[Todd Lowe]]).{{ref|First Taste|E-2}} Tara's story is characterized by her relationship with her [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] and abusive mother [[List of True Blood characters#Lettie Mae Thornton|Lettie Mae]] ([[Adina Porter]]){{ref|First Taste|E-2}} and her own inner \"demons\".{{ref|Wanna Know|E-10}} During the season, Lettie Mae achieves sobriety{{ref|Fourth|E-8}} but Tara's life begins to spin out of control. Kicked out of her home and totaling her car in a drunk driving accident,{{ref|Wanna Know|E-10}} she's taken in by \"social worker\" [[Characters of True Blood#Maryann Forrester|Maryann Forrester]] ([[Michelle Forbes]]).{{ref|Love Bury|E-11}} While staying with Maryann, Tara is introduced to [[List of True Blood characters#Benedict Talley|\"Eggs\" Benedict Talley]] ([[Mehcad Brooks]]), to whom she becomes attracted.{{ref|Love Bury|E-11}}\n\nThe final major plotline of the first season revolves around the elements of vampire society that Sookie and Bill's relationship introduce. While trying to prove her brother's innocence in relation to Maudette and Dawn's murders, Bill takes Sookie to the vampire bar \"Fangtasia\" to investigate. There, Sookie is introduced to Fangtasia's owner and the vampire sheriff of \"Area 5\" in Louisiana: [[Eric Northman]] ([[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]]).{{ref|Dragon House|E-4}} Eric is immediately interested in Sookie and her strange abilities, but his progeny and assistant [[Pamela Swynford De Beaufort|Pam]] ([[Kristin Bauer]]) is less impressed.{{ref|Dragon House|E-4}} Eric employs Sookie to find a thief in his bar, but the perpetrator (a vampire named Longshadow) attempts to kill Sookie when she reveals his identity. Bill stakes and kills the thief to save her, but has committed a serious crime in killing another vampire.{{ref|Fourth|E-8}} When Bill is tried for his crime, his punishment is to transform seventeen-year-old [[Jessica Hamby]] ([[Deborah Ann Woll]]) into a vampire to replace the one he destroyed.{{ref|Wanna Know|E-10}}\n\nA secondary plotline introduced in the first season (which later becomes a main plotline in Season 2) is that although many humans are attracted to vampires (referred to as \"fang bangers\") and flock to establishments like Fangtasia, not all people are accepting of the idea that vampires should be given rights equal to those afforded the mortals of the ''True Blood'' universe. During the first season, one of the ways in which anti-vampire sentiment is expressed is through regular televised appearances by the \"Fellowship of the Sun\",{{ref|First Taste|E-2}} a Dallas-based church that in Season 2 becomes headed by the [[Characters of True Blood#Steve Newlin|Reverend Steve Newlin]] ([[Michael McMillian]]){{ref|Mine|E-3}} after his father and family are killed in a strange \"accident\".{{ref|First Taste|E-2}}\n\nDuring the [[True Blood (season 2)|second season of ''True Blood'']], the influence of Maryann Forrester and the conflict between vampires and humans is expanded. Most of the cast from the first season returns and several new main characters are introduced. The same style of interconnected storytelling used in the first season is repeated, with the foremost plot focusing on Maryann Forrester being revealed as a [[maenad]]{{ref|Release|E-19}} with the power to influence humans.{{ref|Scratches|E-15}} She begins by manipulating Tara and Eggs to achieve her goal of summoning her god to earth,{{ref|Timebomb|E-20}} and eventually takes control of almost the entire population of Bon Temps.{{ref|New World|E-22}}\n\nWhile Maryann begins establishing her hold on Bon Temps, Sookie is recruited by Eric{{ref|Scratches|E-15}} to investigate the disappearance of his two-thousand-year-old maker and the Sheriff of Area 9 in Texas: [[List of True Blood Characters#Godric|Godric]] ([[Allan Hyde]]).{{ref|Never Let|E-17}} While Sookie is absent from Bon Temps, Sam hires [[Characters of True Blood#Daphne Landry|Daphne Landry]] ([[Ashley Jones]]) to join Merlotte's staff.{{ref|Nothing but|E-13}} Daphne (who is revealed to also be a shapeshifter{{ref|Never Let|E-17}}) begins a romance with Sam,{{ref|Fingerpop|E-16}} but is later exposed as working for Maryann.{{ref|Hannah|E-18}} Jason also leaves Bon Temps for Dallas to join the Fellowship of the Sun,{{ref|Party Going|E-14}} which Reverend Newlin has steered in a new militant direction despite the protestations of his wife [[Characters of True Blood#Sarah Newlin|Sarah]] ([[Anna Camp]]).{{ref|Nothing but|E-13}} Godric is discovered in the custody of the Fellowship,{{ref|Never Let|E-17}} and one of Godric's lieutenants, [[List of True Blood characters#Isabel Beaumont|Isabel Beaumont]] ([[Valerie Cruz]]),{{ref|Never Let|E-17}} sends her human boyfriend Hugo ([[Christopher Gartin]]){{ref|Hannah|E-18}} to assist Sookie in infiltrating the church. Though Eric's primary interest in Dallas is finding Godric, he also attempts to place himself between Sookie and Bill. To accomplish this, he enlists the aid of Bill's maker [[Characters of True Blood#Lorena|Lorena]] ([[Mariana Klaveno]]);{{ref|Never Let|E-17}}, who thus becomes a more prominent contribution to the cast after a brief introduction in the first season.{{ref|Sparks|E-5}} In the penultimate episode of the second season, once the conflict in Texas is concluded, the vampire queen of Louisiana [[Sophie-Anne Leclerq]] ([[Evan Rachel Wood]]) is introduced.{{ref|Frenzy|E-23}} Both Bill and Eric visit her in an attempt to find out how to defeat Maryann.{{ref|Frenzy|E-23}} Bill uses the information provided by Sophie-Anne to devise a plan involving Sam and Sookie, and the three manage to kill Maryann in the season two finale. Subsequently, Bill takes Sookie out to an exclusive French restaurant to propose to her. However, before she can give her answer, Bill is kidnapped.\n\nSeason three picks up straight after the events of season two with Sookie on the hunt to track down Bill and his kidnappers. She turns to Eric for help, who is not interested (seeing this turn of events as a chance to get Sookie for himself), but he ends up sending werewolf [[Alcide Herveaux]] ([[Joe Manganiello]]) for assistance after it is revealed that Bill was taken by V-addicted werewolves in the employ of the 3000-year-old vampire king of Mississippi, [[List of True Blood characters#Seasonal antagonists|Russell Edgington]] ([[Denis O'Hare]]). Meanwhile, back in Bon Temps, Lafayette embarks on a relationship with his mother's care nurse and [[Brujer\u00eda|brujo]] [[List of True Blood characters|Jes\u00fas Velasquez]] ([[Kevin Alejandro]]) and learns about his own special powers as a medium, while Sam hires a new waitress at Merlotte's, Wiccan Holly Cleary ([[Lauren Bowles]]).\n\nIn season 4, [[Jessica Tuck]] ([[List of True Blood characters#Nan Flanagan|Nan Flanagan]]) and [[Janina Gavankar]] (Luna) became season regulars. [[Alexandra Breckenridge]] (Kate) and Vedette Lim (Naomi) became recurring actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvguide.com/News/True-Blood-Tuck-1026065.aspx|title= True Blood Promotes Jessica Tuck; Adds Three New Actresses|publisher=TVGuide.com|accessdate=November 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nJoining the cast for season five was [[Christopher Meloni]], who previously starred on another of [[HBO]]'s own original series ''[[Oz (TV series)|Oz]]'' as well as ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' for 12 years. Details on his character have yet to be released.<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/12/13/chris-meloni-joins-true-blood/|title= Chris Meloni to play old vampire on 'True Blood'|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=December 13, 2011}}</ref> Also joining the cast is [[Scott Foley]] as Patrick, Terry's old war buddy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://true-blood.net/2011/06/21/true-blood-season-5-casting-news-spoilers/ |title=True Blood Season 5 Casting News (SPOILERS!) &#124; True-Blood.net \u2013 True Blood season 5 news, spoilers, & photos! |date=June 21, 2011 |accessdate=February 10, 2012}}</ref> Louis Herthum as JD, [[Kelly Overton (actress)|Kelly Overton]] as Rikki, a new werewolf curious how Marcus died,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://truebloodnet.com/spoiler-new-weres-cast-for-true-blood-season-5/ |title=Spoiler: New Weres Cast for True Blood Season 5 |publisher=Truebloodnet.com |date=December 4, 2011 |accessdate=February 10, 2012}}</ref> [[Carolyn Hennesy]] is expected to be Rosalyn Harris, a Texas vampire with twang,<ref>{{cite web|author=Kelly Woo |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/true-blood/articles/carolyn-hennesy-joining-true-blood-season-5-cast |title=True Blood Season 5 News: Carolyn Hennesy Cast as ''Vampire With Texas Twang'' \u2013 True Blood |publisher=Wetpaint.com |date= |accessdate=February 10, 2012}}</ref> and Jacob Hopkins will play child vampire Chancellor Alexander Drew.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jerrica Tisdale |url=http://gossipandgab.com/5673/true-blood-season-5-exclusive-interview-with-jacob-hopkins |title=True Blood 2012: Season 5 Exclusive Interview with Jacob Hopkins |publisher=GossipandGab.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor season six, it was announced that [[Robert Kazinsky]] would join the principal cast as Ben, a faerie and a potential love interest for Sookie. He will also help Sookie and Jason discover the truth about their parents' murders.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/13/the-good-wife-kyle-maclachlan_n_2125865.html |title='The Good Wife' Nabs Kyle MacLachlan And More Casting News |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=June 23, 2013 |first=Jaimie |last=Etkin}}</ref> [[Robert Patrick]], who guest starred in season five as Jackson Herveaux, was promoted to series regular for season six.<ref name=\"ign.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/12/10/robert-patrick-becomes-true-blood-regular?abthid=50c636e213459c776e000004 |title=Robert Patrick Becomes True Blood Regular |website=IGN |date=December 10, 2012 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref> [[Rutger Hauer]], who starred in popular films such as [[Blade Runner]] and [[Batman Begins]], was announced as a series regular playing Macklyn, a character with \"strong ties to Sookie and Jason.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/true-blood-season-6-rutger-hauer/ |title='True Blood' Season 6: Rutger Hauer Added As Series Regular |publisher=Screencrush.com |date=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs reported by ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', [[Adina Porter]] would be returning for the seventh season as a series regular after being credited as a Special Guest Star since season two. Also upgraded to regulars are season six guest stars [[Amelia Rose Blaire]] as Willa Burrell, [[Bailey Noble]] as Adilyn Bellefleur, [[Luke Grimes]] as James and [[Karolina Wydra]] as Violet Mazurski.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/true-blood-promotes-adina-porter-651066 |title='True Blood' Promotes Adina Porter to Series Regular |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Season synopsis==\n{{Main|List of True Blood episodes|l1=List of ''True Blood'' episodes}}\n{{Anchor|Plot}}\n\n===Season 1 (2008)===\n{{Main|True Blood (season 1)}}\nThe main mystery of the first season concerns the murders of women connected to Sookie's brother, Jason. Maudette Pickens and Dawn Green are both strangled shortly after having been alone with him.. Though Detective Bellefleur has little doubt that Jason is the killer, the town sheriff does not suspect him. Sookie's grandmother is murdered shortly afterward. After the murders, Jason becomes addicted to vampire blood and has a short relationship with another addict, Amy Burley, which ends when she is murdered as well. The season also focuses on Sookie's relationship with Bill and Sam's relationship with Sookie's friend Tara. Bill explains the rules of being a vampire to Sookie and, after killing a vampire to defend her, is forced to \"turn\" a young girl named Jessica into a vampire as punishment. The immature Jessica is left under Bill's care and starts to grow up both as a vampire and as a person. In the end, it is revealed that Arlene Fowler's fianc\u00e9, Rene Lenier, has been killing women who associate with vampires. Further, he is actually a man named Drew Marshall who created a false identity, complete with a fake Cajun accent. The season ends with the discovery of a body in Detective Andy Bellefleur's car in Merlotte's parking lot.\n\n===Season 2 (2009)===\n{{Main|True Blood (season 2)}}\nThe second season loosely follows the plot of the second novel of ''[[The Southern Vampire Mysteries]]'', ''[[Living Dead in Dallas]]''. In addition, the character of [[Sophie-Anne Leclerq]], initially introduced in the sixth novel ''[[Definitely Dead]]'', was introduced as a major supporting character. The main theme of the season involves the disappearance of [[Godric(True Blood Tv Series)|Godric]], the 2,000-year-old vampire Sheriff of Area 9. [[Eric Northman|Eric]] enlists Sookie and Bill's aid in finding the ancient vampire in Dallas. Their paths cross Jason's as he seeks to discover meaning in his life with the Fellowship of the Sun, a church dedicated to anti-vampire activities. A second theme concerns a [[maenad]] named [[Characters of True Blood#Maryann Forrester|Maryann]] who visits Bon Temps after [[Characters of True Blood#Tara Thornton|Tara]] attracts her attention at the end of the first season. Maryann is a figure from [[Characters of True Blood#Sam Merlotte|Sam]]'s past and knows his true identity as a shapeshifter. Her influence on the town and its residents results in mayhem that grows more destructive as the season progresses. At the end of the season, Bill proposes to Sookie but is kidnapped by unknown assailants when Sookie retreats to the bathroom to consider his proposal.\n\n===Season 3 (2010)===\n{{Main|True Blood (season 3)}}\nSeason three loosely follows the plot of the third novel of The Southern Vampire Mysteries, ''[[Club Dead]]'', and introduces [[werewolves]] to the show's mythology through Alcide, a werewolf hired by Eric to help Sookie find Bill. It also introduces the characters of [[List of True Blood characters#Russell Edgington|Russell Edgington]], the Vampire King of Mississippi, who wishes to overturn the Vampire Authority. In addition, some characters from the fourth novel ''[[Dead to the World (novel)|Dead to the World]]'' are introduced: [[List of The Southern Vampire Mysteries characters#Stackhouse|Crystal Norris]] as Jason's love interest, her family of [[werecat|werepanthers]] from Hotshot, and Sookie's \"faerie godmother\", Claudine. Sookie's heritage as part [[faerie]] is also revealed later in the season, a major plot element from the eighth and ninth novels ''[[From Dead to Worse]]'' and ''[[Dead and Gone (novel)|Dead and Gone]]''. This season ends with Jason left to take care of the werepanthers of Hotshot, Tara leaving Bon Temps after a traumatic experience with a vampire, Sookie discovering that Bill was first sent to Bon Temps by the Vampire Queen of Louisiana, Sam shooting his brother, Tommy, and Hoyt and Jessica moving in together. The final cliffhanger involves Claudine taking Sookie away to the land of Faerie.\n\n===Season 4 (2011)===\n{{Main|True Blood (season 4)}}\nA coven of witches, led by Marnie, poses a threat to vampires when they discover the witches are working on necromancy. Sookie returns to Bon Temps after a year (even though for her she was away for only a few minutes in Faerie) to find Bill as the new King of Louisiana and that her brother and friends had given up hope of finding her. As the series progresses, a powerful necromancer from the 16th century, Antonia, possesses the body of Marnie in order to exact revenge on all vampires. Sookie starts a romance with Eric who has amnesia due to a spell cast by Antonia/Marnie. The witch Antonia eventually realizes the wrongdoing she's caused to innocent people and decides to stop. Yet Marnie, addicted to Antonia's power, binds her against her will to acquire her powers. Subplots include Lafayette's introduction to the world of magic and his abilities as a medium, Sam's family troubles, Alcide and Debbie's troubled relationship, and Jason, Hoyt and Jessica's love triangle. The finale is a series of cliffhangers, including a warning from the ghost of Rene that Terry will cause Arlene trouble, the escape of Russell Edgington, the reappearance of Steve Newlin as a vampire, and the shooting of Tara.\n\n===Season 5 (2012)===\n{{Main|True Blood (season 5)}}\nThe season starts with Sookie and Lafayette asking for Pam to turn Tara into a vampire. Bill and Eric are captured by the Vampire Authority for killing Nan Flanagan. The two are almost sentenced to death by the Guardian, Roman, before revealing that Russell Edgington is alive and free after being released by a mysterious vampire. With the help of Sookie, the team discovers his hiding place and brings him in. Russell and his new vampire-companion, Steve Newlin, along with Salome, and Eric's vampire sister, Nora, redefine the values of the Authority and view humans as nothing more than food: just as Lilith of the Vampire bible wanted. Meanwhile, Alcide deals with his troubled rise to pack-master, Terry learns he is death-cursed after committing a terrible crime during the war in [[Iraq]], while Tara learns how to deal with her newly given life as Pam's progeny. Jason and Sookie discover that their parents were murdered by a vampire named Warlow. Hoyt gets involved with a hate group, then decides to leave for Alaska, just as Andy heads towards life as a family man, and Lafayette tries to deal with the powers given to him by Jesus. The season ends with the Authority leadership being wiped out during the True Blood crisis, and Bill drinking the entirety of the sacred vial of Lilith in front of Sookie and Eric. He soon meets the \"true death\", but shortly after, he \"rises from the blood\", as an even more powerful vampire reincarnation of Lilith (\"Billith\").\n\n===Season 6 (2013)===\n{{Main|True Blood (season 6)}}\nThe sixth season of ''True Blood'' premiered on June 16, 2013. After Alan Ball's departure from the series at the end of season 5, [[Brian Buckner]] replaced Ball as the show's showrunner. Season six focuses on Bill's abilities after he had drunk Lilith's blood. Sookie and Jason try to find Warlow, the vampire who killed their parents, with a fairy grandfather named Niall who arrives in Bon Temps while a new Louisiana governor leads a platform to eradicate the entire vampire race with Sarah Newlin. Sam and Alcide fight for Emma's safety; Terry struggles to live with himself after having killed Patrick; Andy raises his fairy daughters. Eric decides to turn the governor's daughter into a vampire to convince him to stop his campaign, but she is put into a vampire camp along with Eric, Pam, Jessica, and Tara, where they are all supposed to meet the sun. Bill asks Sookie for help, who is considering becoming Warlow's vampire-fairy bride after discovering her parents tried to kill her when she was young. Both of them go to the vampire camp, where Eric has discovered that Sarah Newlin created a virus that kills vampires, later witnessing Sarah infect Nora in front of him. When the vampires are about to meet the sun, Bill offers his blood to them, allowing them to walk in the daylight. The season finishes six months later where Sookie is dating Alcide, Bill has released a book about the effects of drinking Lilith's blood, and Sam being the mayor of Bon Temps and gibing his bar to Arlene, and a group of infected vampires heading toward the bar.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Sarene Leeds |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/q-a-true-blood-showrunner-brian-buckner-spills-on-season-six-20130610 |title=QA: 'True Blood' Showrunner on Season Six &#124; Movies News |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=June 10, 2013 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Season 7 (2014)===\n{{main|True Blood (season 7)}}\nThe seventh and final season premiered on June 22, 2014, with the last episode was airing on August 24, 2014. In this season, Bon Temps is terrorized by a group of vampires infected with the virus created in the previous season. They kill Tara and kidnap Arlene, Holly, and Nicole. Pam travels the world in search of Eric, who is found in France infected by the virus. They meet Sookie, Bill, Jessica, and Alcide in Bon Temps and rescue the people who were kidnapped, which results in Alcide's death and Sookie being infected by the virus and transmitting it to Bill. Eric and Pam search for Sarah Newlin, who supposedly has an antidote for the virus. Several characters encounter closure like Lettie Mae making peace with Tara through visions caused by vampire blood, Jessica and Hoyt getting married after reuniting during the season, Lafayette entering a relationship with Jessica's ex-boyfriend, James, and Sam leaving Bon Temps with Nicole. At the end of the series, Bill refuses to take the antidote to heal himself from the virus and asks Sookie to give him the \"ultimate kindness\". Sookie then strikes Bill's heart with a wooden stick. Pam and Eric successfully sell the new Tru Blood with the antidote. The last scene of the series shows a pregnant Sookie sitting outside on a table full of people beside a mysterious man. They kiss and drink, and everyone around them appears to be happy.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; text-align:center; margin:10px\"\n|+ [[Metacritic]] ratings per season\n|-\n|{{Graph:Chart\n| width = 230\n| height = 150\n| xType = string\n| xAxisTitle = Season\n| x = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7\n| yAxisMax = 100 | yAxisMin = 0 | showSymbols = | yGrid = \n| yAxisTitle = Rating\n| y = 63, 74, 79, 74, 74, 58, 54\n}}\n|-\n|<!-- begin inner table -->\n{| style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=row | Season\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 1)|1]]\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 2)|2]]\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 3)|3]]\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 4)|4]]\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 5)|5]]\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 6)|6]]\n| scope=col | [[True Blood (season 7)|7]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Rating\n| {{formatnum:63}}<ref name=MetacriticS1>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 1 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/ }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:74}}<ref name=MetacriticS2>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 2 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/season-2 }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:79}}<ref name=MetacriticS3>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 3 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/season-3 }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:74}}<ref name=MetacriticS4>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 4 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/season-4 }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:74}}<ref name=MetacriticS5>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 5 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/season-5 }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:58}}<ref name=MetacriticS6>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 6 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/season-6 }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:54}}<ref name=MetacriticS7>{{cite web |title=True Blood: Season 7 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/true-blood/season-7 }}</ref>\n|}\n<!-- end inner table -->\n|}\n\nThe series has an approval rating of 70 percent on the [[review aggregator]] website Rotten Tomatoes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/true_blood|title=True Blood|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\nThe first season of ''True Blood'' received positive reviews, despite initial impressions being mixed. Linda Stasi of the ''[[New York Post]]'' wrote of the opening episodes: \n\n<blockquote>If HBO's new vampire show is any indication, there would still be countless deaths \u2013 especially among vampire hunters and the viewers who love them \u2013 because everyone would be dying of boredom. And so it is with HBO's new series from death-obsessed Alan Ball, creator of the legendary ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', whose new show ''True Blood'', won't so much make your blood run cold as it will leave you cold.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.nypost.com/seven/09052008/tv/bloody_murder_127515.htm| title = Bloody Murder: It's the normal people who really suck| author = Stasi, Linda| date = September 5, 2008| accessdate=June 13, 2009\n| newspaper = [[New York Post]]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nRobert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' concluded: \n\n<blockquote>Sexy, witty and unabashedly peculiar, ''True Blood'' is a blood-drenched [[Southern Gothic]] romantic parable set in a world where vampires are out and about and campaigning for equal rights. Part mystery, part fantasy, part comedy, and all wildly imaginative exaggeration, ''[True] Blood'' proves that there's still vibrant life \u2014 or death \u2014 left in the '[[star-crossed]] cute lovers' paradigm. You just have to know where to stake your romantic claim.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2008-09-04-true-blood_N.htm?csp=34| title = HBO gets an infusion of Oh-positive 'Blood'| author = Bianco, Robert| date = September 9, 2008|accessdate=June 13, 2009| newspaper = [[USA Today]]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe series achieved its highest Rotten Tomatoes rating of 95%, with an average rating of 8.25/10 based on 22 reviews, during its third season. The critical consensus of the season reads, \"''True Blood'' seems to fully understand its appeal, and its third season provides plenty of graphic thrills, steamy romance, and biting satire for its fans.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/true_blood/s03|title=True Blood: Season 3|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], another aggregator of critical responses, found \"generally favorable reviews\" for the first five seasons, with ratings of 63, 74, 79, 74 and 74, respectively.<ref name=MetacriticS1/><ref name=MetacriticS2/><ref name=MetacriticS3/><ref name=MetacriticS4/><ref name=MetacriticS5/>\n\nThe sixth season, notable for being the first of the series not to have [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]] as showrunner, was met with mixed reviews in contrast to the acclaim of the previous five seasons. Many critics noted the decreasing quality of the scripts and production values. In his review, Brian Lowry of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' remarked:\n<blockquote>People can debate when \u201c''True Blood''\u2019s\u201d creative rigor mortis officially set in \u2014 somewhere during that stretch when the show began piling one supernatural creature upon another (werewolves and witches and faeries, oh my!) \u2014 but suffice it to say this once-significant and hugely lucrative HBO series limps into its seventh and final season looking pretty anemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/reviews/tv-review-true-blood-1201218816/|title=TV Review: 'True Blood'|first=Brian|last=Lowry|website=Variety|date=June 18, 2014}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe sixth and seven seasons each received an approval rating of 44% on Rotten Tomatoes, with the critical consensus of season six reading: \"A major letdown coming off the end of season five, ''True Blood'' seems to be running out of steam and isn't aging as elegantly as its eternal vampires.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/true_blood/s06|title=True Blood: Season 6|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/true_blood/s07|title=True Blood: Season 7|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> On Metacritic, the sixth season rated 58, while the seventh 54, both indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref name=MetacriticS6/><ref name=MetacriticS7/>\n\nThe cast received positive reviews for their performances, with praise going to the performances of [[Anna Paquin]] and [[Nelsan Ellis]]. For the first season, [[Anna Paquin]] won the Best Performance by an Actress in a Television Series \u2013 Drama [[Golden Globe]] at the [[66th Golden Globe Awards]]; she was also nominated the next year and won the [[Saturn Award]] for Best Actress in a Series, Drama at the [[13th Satellite Awards]], a ceremony in which [[Nelsan Ellis]] also won Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film. [[Stephen Moyer]] won the award for Best Actor on Television at the 2010 ceremony.\n\n===Cultural influence===\n''True Blood'' was the subject of a ''Sesame Street'' sketch parody titled \"True Mud\" (2010), featuring puppet versions of Sookie, Bill, Lafayette, Sam, Tara, and Sheriff Dearborn. In the skit, Muppet Sookie struggles to fulfill Muppet Bill's pleas for a pint of \"True Mud\", as the other characters speculate whether or not he is a \"grouch\".<ref>CBC News, September 27, 2010 \"[http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/things-that-go-pop-blog/2010/09/sesame-street-parodies-true-blood.html CBC.ca]\"\n</ref>\n\nAnna Paquin (Sookie), Stephen Moyer (Bill), and Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd (Eric) appeared on the August 2010 cover of ''Rolling Stone'' covered in blood and completely naked. This cover drew criticism<ref name=\"aoltv1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aoltv.com/2010/08/18/true-blood-stars-naked-on-the-cover-of-rolling-stone/ |title='True Blood' Rolling Stone Cover: Bloody Hot or Too Gruesome? |publisher=Aoltv.com |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref> due to the image's supposed promotion of sexuality and violence. The show's creator, Alan Ball, stated in the magazine, \"To me, vampires are sex... I don't get a vampire story about abstinence. I'm 53. I don't care about high school students. I find them irritating and uninformed.\"<ref name=\"aoltv1\"/>\n\n===Comparisons to LGBT rights===\nThe struggle for vampire equality in ''True Blood'' has been interpreted as an allegory for the [[LGBT social movements|LGBT rights movement]].<ref name=\"entertainment weekly\">{{cite news|author=Ken Tucker |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20284276,00.html |title=True Blood Reviewed|publisher=Entertainment Weekly.com|date=June 10, 2009 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> [[Charlaine Harris]], the author of the [[The Southern Vampire Mysteries|book series]] on which the show is based, stated that her initial characterization for the vampires were as \"...a minority that was trying to get equal rights\".<ref name=\"gayrights1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090626003421/http://www.nypost.com/seven/06232009/tv/flesh__blood_175586.htm \"Flesh & 'Blood': How HBO series has turned hot vampires into gay rights analogy\"], [[New York Post]], June 23, 2009. Retrieved June 30, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"NPR review\">[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94320825 \"'True Blood,' Tasty New TV From Alan Ball And HBO\"], [[National Public Radio]], May 4, 2009. Retrieved May 5, 2010.</ref> Several phrases in the series are borrowed and adapted from expressions used against and about [[LGBT]] people, such as \"God Hates Fangs\" ([[Westboro Baptist Church#Views on homosexuality|God Hates Fags]]) and \"Coming out of the coffin\" ([[Coming out|coming out of the closet]]).<ref name=\"NPR review\"/>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Ken Tucker wrote that the show is built \"around a series of metaphors: Vampire rights stand in for gay rights, and now the clever laughs elicited from this bratty-vampire girl represent an extreme of adolescent rebelliousness\".<ref name=\"entertainment weekly\"/> David Bianculli of [[NPR]] wrote, \"''True Blood'' is big on allegory, and the tension about accepting vampires into society is an obvious play on [[civil rights]] in general, and gay rights in particular\".<ref name=\"NPR review\"/> However, the series' creator, [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]], who is gay, has stated that such a comparison is lazy and possibly [[homophobia|homophobic]]; and Lauren Gutterman of the [[Center for Lesbian and Gay Studies]] has expressed concerns that the show might perpetuate negative [[stereotype]]s of homosexuals as deviants.<ref name=\"gayrights1\" />\n\n==Ratings==\n[[File:Viewers of True Blood.png|thumb|400px|right|Graph of the US viewing figures of the first three seasons of ''True Blood''.]]\nThe first episode of ''True Blood'' debuted at a very modest 1.44 million viewers compared to the network's past drama premiers such as ''[[Big Love]]'' which premiered at 4.56 million, and ''[[John from Cincinnati]]'' which debuted at 3.4 million.<ref>Show Tracker. [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2008/09/hbo-premiere-tr.html \"HBO's 'True Blood': Audiences don't bite\"], [[Los Angeles Times]], September 3, 2008. Retrieved January 10, 2009.</ref> However, by late November 2008, 6.8 million a week were watching: this figure included repeat and on-demand viewings.<ref>TV Decoder. [http://tvdecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/23/true-blood-shows-ratings-growth-for-hbo/ \"\u2018True Blood\u2019 Shows Ratings Growth for HBO\"], [[New York Times]], November 23, 2008. Retrieved January 10, 2009.</ref> The season finale's viewership was 2.4 million.\n\nThe second-season premiere of the series (June 14, 2009) was viewed by 3.7 million, making it the most watched program on HBO since the series finale of ''[[The Sopranos]]''. The total number of viewers for the season premiere, including the late night replay, was 5.1 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005012.html?categoryid=14&cs=1|title=Ads help auds bite into 'True Blood'|last=Levine|first=Stuart|date=June 16, 2009|work=Variety|publisher=Reed Elsevier Inc.|accessdate=June 16, 2009}}</ref>\nThe tenth episode of the second season (August 23, 2009) was seen by 5.3 million viewers, a new record for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2009/08/25/true-bloody-momentum-for-true-blood-5-3-million-and-another-record/25336 |title=Updated: True bloody momentum for True Blood: 5.3 million and another record! |publisher=Tvbythenumbers.com |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref> The second season's finale (September 13, 2009) was seen by 5.1 million viewers. An average of 12.4 million a week watched the second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2009/09/19/true-blood-averages-12-4-million-per-episode-across-platforms-in-second-season/27753 |title=True Blood averages 12.4 million per episode across platforms in second season |publisher=Tvbythenumbers.com |date=September 19, 2009 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe ninth episode of the fourth season (August 21, 2011) set a new record with 5.53 million viewers, making it the most viewed episode to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/08/23/sunday-cable-true-blood-kardashians-entourage-lead-breaking-bad-glee-project-much-more/101035/ |title=True Blood,' 'Kardashians,' 'Entourage' Lead + 'Breaking Bad,' 'Glee Project' & Much More |publisher=Tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com |date=August 23, 2011 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''True Blood'' is HBO's most watched series since ''[[The Sopranos]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/arts/television/16arts-VICTORIESFOR_BRF.html|title=Victories for NBC, MTV and 'True Blood'|first=Benjamin Toff; Compiled By Dave|last=Itzkoff|date=September 15, 2009|publisher=|accessdate=March 15, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The show was declared the eighth highest rated show for the first ten years of [[IMDb.com]] Pro (2002\u20132012).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brad-pitt-johnny-depp-dark-knight-lost-imdb-top-10-284912|title=Johnny Depp, 'The Dark Knight,' 'Lost' Named to IMDb's Top 10 of the Last Decade|accessdate=February 10, 2012|date=January 25, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Schillaci, Sophie A.}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. Nielsen ratings===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! style=\"width:20%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Timeslot ([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|ET]]/[[Pacific Time Zone|PT]])\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| # Ep.\n! colspan=2| Premiere\n! colspan=2| Finale\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Aired\n! style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Viewers<br />(in millions)\n|-\n! Date\n! span style=\"width:11%; font-size:smaller; line-height:100%;\"| Premiere<br />Viewers<br />(in millions)\n! Date\n! span style=\"width:11%; font-size:smaller; line-height:100%;\"| Finale<br />Viewers<br />(in millions)\n|-\n! '''[[True Blood (season 1)|Season 1]]'''\n| rowspan=\"7\" | <center>Sundays 9:00pm</center>\n! 12\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>September 7, 2008</center>\n! 1.44<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117991937.html?categoryid=1237&cs=1&query=True+Blood |title= 1.4 million tune into 'True Blood' |last= Frankel |first= Daniel |magazine = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date= September 9, 2008 |accessdate=September 17, 2008}}</ref>\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>November 23, 2008</center>\n! 2.45<ref>{{cite news|last=Kissell |first=Rick |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117996475.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 |title=True Blood Season 1 Finale Ratings |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 25, 2008 |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref>\n! style=\"font-size:smaller\"| 2008\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\"|2.00\n|-\n! '''[[True Blood (season 2)|Season 2]]'''\n! 12\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>June 14, 2009</center>\n! 3.70<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/294649-Cable_Ratings_True_Blood_Delivers_For_HBO.php?rssid=20065 |title= 'True Blood' delivers for HBO|magazine = Broadcasting & Cable |date= June 16, 2009 |accessdate=June 17, 2009}}</ref>\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>September 13, 2009</center>\n! 5.11<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2009/09/15/cable-ratings-usc-vmas-icarly-and-true-bloodfinale/27176|title=True Blood finale audience doubles last season's ender|publisher=TVbytheNumbers|date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=September 14, 2010}}</ref>\n! style=\"font-size:smaller\"| 2009\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\"|4.28\n|-\n! '''[[True Blood (season 3)|Season 3]]'''\n! 12\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>June 13, 2010</center>\n! 5.10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/06/15/hbos-true-blood-premiere-ratings-up-38/54173 |title=HBO's 'True Blood' Premiere Ratings Up 38% \u2013 TV Ratings, Nielsen Ratings, Television Show Ratings |publisher=TVbytheNumbers.com |date=June 15, 2010 |accessdate=June 29, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>September 12, 2010</center>\n! 5.38<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/|title=TV By The Numbers by zap2it.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref>\n! style=\"font-size:smaller\"| 2010\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\"|4.97\n|-\n! '''[[True Blood (season 4)|Season 4]]'''\n! 12\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>June 26, 2011</center>\n! 5.42\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>September 11, 2011</center>\n! 5.05\n! style=\"font-size:smaller\"| 2011\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\"|4.97\n|-\n! '''[[True Blood (season 5)|Season 5]]'''\n! 12\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>June 10, 2012</center>\n! 5.20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/06/12/sunday-cable-ratings-true-blood-wins-night-mad-men-longmire-the-client-list-the-glades-drop-dead-diva-more/137638/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'True Blood' Wins 