y:Concepts in physics]]\n[[Category:Light]]\n[[Category:Special relativity|Light]]\n[[Category:Units of velocity]]\n", "name_user": "Alex Devens", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speed_of_light"}
{"title_page": "Bustin' Out", "text_new": "{{about|the album|the song by Material|Bustin' Out (song)|The Sims game with the same subtitle|The Sims Bustin' Out}}\n\n{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Bustin' Out\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Pure Prairie League]]\n| cover      = Pure Prairie League - Bustin' Out.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 1972\n| recorded   = RCA Studios, Toronto\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]], [[folk rock]]\n| length     = 34:36\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = Robert Alan Ringe\n| prev_title = [[Pure Prairie League (album)|Pure Prairie League]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Two Lane Highway]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Bustin' Out\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Amie (song)|Amie]]\n | single1date = 1973\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score =  {{Rating|5|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r15920|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Bustin' Out''''' is the second album by [[United States|American]] [[country rock]] band [[Pure Prairie League]], released by [[RCA Records]] in 1972. The album ended up becoming far more popular a couple of years after its release, during the height of the [[Country Rock]], and [[Southern Rock]] boom of the mid-1970s. By then, band leader [[Craig Fuller]] was no longer in the band due to draft board issues. \n\n\"Amie\" was released as a single in 1973, and began receiving airplay mostly on college radio stations. \"Falling In and Out of Love\" ends in a [[segue]] to \"Amie\", which then concludes with the main chorus of \"Falling In and Out of Love.\"  Because of this interrelationship, many American classic rock and AOR radio stations play the pair of songs as a single track. \n\nThe album features a guest appearance by lead guitarist [[Mick Ronson]] on the track \"Angel #9\".\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by Craig Fuller, except where noted.\n#\"Jazzman\" (Ed Holstein)&nbsp;\u2013 2:34\n#\"Angel #9\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:55\n#\"Leave My Heart Alone\" (George Powell)&nbsp;\u2013 4:24\n#\"Early Morning Riser\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:05\n#\"Falling In and Out of Love\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:12\n#\"[[Amie (song)|Amie]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:18\n#\"Boulder Skies\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:01\n#\"Angel\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:26\n#\"Call Me, Tell Me\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:41\n\n==Personnel==\n;Pure Prairie League\n*[[Craig Fuller]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[electric guitar]], vocals\n*George Ed Powell&nbsp;\u2013 electric guitar, vocals\n*William Frank Hinds&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n;Additional musicians\n*Michael Connor&nbsp;\u2013 [[piano]], [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*James Rolleston&nbsp;\u2013 bass\n*Al Brisco&nbsp;\u2013 [[steel guitar]]\n*[[Mick Ronson]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, background vocals, string arrangements\n*Dianne Brooks&nbsp;\u2013 background vocals on \"Leave My Heart Alone\"\n*Little Bobby Ring[e]&nbsp;\u2013 [[marimba]], [[Shaker (musical instrument)|shaker]]\n\n;Production\n*Producer: Robert Alan Ringe\n*Engineer: Mark Smith\n*Recording Technician: Cub Richardson\n*Digital Producer: Susan Ruskin\n*Digital Series Executive Producer: Don Wardell\n*Remastering: Rick Rowe\n*Art direction: Acy Lehman\n*Management: Roger Abramson\n\n==Charts==\n'''Album'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] (United States)\n{| border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=2 width=\"550px\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1975\n|align=\"left\"|Pop Albums\n|align=\"left\"|34\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Singles''' - [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n{| border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=2 width=\"550px\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Song\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1975\n|align=\"left\"|Amie\n|align=\"left\"|27\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Bustin' Out of L Seven]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pure Prairie League}}\n\n[[Category:Pure Prairie League albums]]\n[[Category:1972 albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Norman Rockwell]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the album|the song by Material|Bustin' Out (song)|The Sims game with the same subtitle|The Sims Bustin' Out}}\n\n{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Bustin' Out\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Pure Prairie League]]\n| cover      = Pure Prairie League - Bustin' Out.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 1972\n| recorded   = RCA Studios, Toronto\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]], [[folk rock]]\n| length     = 34:36\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = Robert Alan Ringe\n| prev_title = [[Pure Prairie League (album)|Pure Prairie League]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Two Lane Highway]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Bustin' Out\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Amie (song)|Amie]]\n | single1date = 1973\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score =  {{Rating|5|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r15920|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Bustin' Out''''' is the second album by [[United States|American]] [[country rock]] band [[Pure Prairie League]], released by [[RCA Records]] in 1972. The album ended up becoming far more popular a couple of years after its release, during the height of the [[Country Rock]], and [[Southern Rock]] boom of the mid-1970s. By then, band leader [[Craig Fuller]] was no longer in the band due to draft board issues. \n\n\"Amie\" was released as a single in 1973, and began receiving airplay mostly on college radio stations. \"Falling In and Out of Love\" ends in a [[segue]] to \"Amie\", which then concludes with the main chorus of \"Falling In and Out of Love.\"  Because of this interrelationship, many American classic rock and AOR radio stations play the pair of songs as a single track. \n\nThe album features a guest appearance by lead guitarist [[Mick Ronson]] on the track \"Angel #9\".\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by Craig Fuller, except where noted.\n#\"Jazzman\" (Ed Holstein)&nbsp;\u2013 2:34\n#\"Angel #9\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:55\n#\"Leave My Heart Alone\" (George Powell)&nbsp;\u2013 4:24\n#\"Early Morning Riser\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:05\n#\"Falling In and Out of Love\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:12\n#\"[[Amie (song)|Amie]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:18\n#\"Boulder Skies\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:01\n#\"Angel\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:26\n#\"Call Me, Tell Me\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:41\n\n==Personnel==\n;Pure Prairie League\n*[[Craig Fuller]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[electric guitar]], vocals\n*George Ed Powell&nbsp;\u2013 electric guitar, vocals\n*William Frank Hinds&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n;Additional musicians\n*Michael Connor&nbsp;\u2013 [[piano]], [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*James Rolleston&nbsp;\u2013 bass\n*Al \"Brisco\" Clark&nbsp;\u2013 [[steel guitar]]\n*[[Mick Ronson]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, background vocals, string arrangements\n*Dianne Brooks&nbsp;\u2013 background vocals on \"Leave My Heart Alone\"\n*Little Bobby Ring[e]&nbsp;\u2013 [[marimba]], [[Shaker (musical instrument)|shaker]]\n\n;Production\n*Producer: Robert Alan Ringe\n*Engineer: Mark Smith\n*Recording Technician: Cub Richardson\n*Digital Producer: Susan Ruskin\n*Digital Series Executive Producer: Don Wardell\n*Remastering: Rick Rowe\n*Art direction: Acy Lehman\n*Management: Roger Abramson\n\n==Charts==\n'''Album'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] (United States)\n{| border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=2 width=\"550px\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1975\n|align=\"left\"|Pop Albums\n|align=\"left\"|34\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Singles''' - [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n{| border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=2 width=\"550px\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Song\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1975\n|align=\"left\"|Amie\n|align=\"left\"|27\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Bustin' Out of L Seven]]''\n\n==References==\n